---
import BaseLayout from '~/layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
import Ornament from '~/components/ui/Ornament.astro';
import Badge from '~/components/ui/Badge.astro';
---
{/* TODO: confirm exact Xpress model/length with Captain Mack. */}
<BaseLayout
  title="M.V. Hush Puppy"
  description="The M.V. Hush Puppy. The smallest vessel of the Miccosukee Yacht Club: a camo Xpress aluminum jon boat with a surface-drive mud motor, captained by Fairy Mack Lane. Native to the slow water and the cypress shade."
  active="about"
>

  <section class="vessel-header">
    <div class="container">
      <a href="/#fleet" class="back-link">&larr; The Fleet</a>
      <div class="vessel-badges">
        <Badge tone="brass">Jon Boat &middot; Xpress Aluminum</Badge>
        <Badge tone="paper">Mud Motor</Badge>
        <Badge tone="paper">Backwater</Badge>
      </div>
      <h1>M.V. Hush Puppy</h1>
      <p class="lead vessel-lead">
        The smallest vessel of the Club, and the one most likely to be found where the
        chartplotter gives up. A camo Xpress aluminum jon boat in the keeping of Captain
        Mack, propelled by a surface-drive mud motor and suited to the slow water, the
        cypress shade, and the sort of fishing that does not require a witness.
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="vessel-photo-full">
    <img src="/assets/macks-jon-side.jpg" alt="Captain Mack's Xpress jon boat on the trailer" />
  </section>

  <section class="section">
    <div class="narrow">

      <h2>The Vessel</h2>
      <p>
        An Xpress aluminum jon, built on a flat-bottom hull that draws only what the paint
        adds to it. Xpress has been welding hulls in Hot Springs, Arkansas since 1966,
        and the result is the sort of boat that takes a stump strike, a sandbar, and an
        inattentive trailer rollback without complaint. The camo finish was applied in
        the spirit of the boat's actual employment, which is not yachting.
      </p>
      <p>
        Power comes from a tiller-steered surface-drive mud motor mounted at the transom.
        The configuration trades top speed for the ability to run in water that would
        embarrass a conventional outboard, and it suits the program. Where the Porkchop
        Express requires a ramp and the Nomine Carens requires a channel, this boat
        requires neither, and proceeds accordingly.
      </p>

      <Ornament />

      <h2>On the Water</h2>
      <p>
        Her usual grounds are the creeks and backwaters of the Big Bend, where the tide
        moves quietly through the grass and the cypress trees stand close enough to make
        navigation a matter of patience rather than speed. She is at her best in the early
        hours, before the heat sets in, with a rod in the boat and no particular destination.
      </p>
      <p>
        Captain Mack has been known to disappear into water no other Club vessel could
        follow, and to return at an hour of his choosing with a quiet report and a cooler
        of evidence. The Club does not require him to explain himself further.
      </p>

      <div class="bow-shot">
        <img src="/assets/macks-jon-bow.jpg" alt="Bow quarter view of Captain Mack's jon boat" />
      </div>

      <Ornament />

      <h2>On the Captain</h2>
      <p>
        Captain Mack stood the longest watch on the passage from Tarpon Springs, holding
        the helm of the <em>Nomine Carens</em> through rain and confused seas while the
        rest of the crew slept. The Club acknowledges that debt formally and on the record.
        That he keeps a small aluminum boat for small water is consistent with the man.
      </p>

      <Ornament />

      <h2>On the Name</h2>
      <p>
        The vessel is named the <em>Hush Puppy</em>, after the fried cornmeal dropped
        into the grease alongside whatever has been pulled out of the water that morning.
        The name was selected with several considerations in mind. The Club's other power
        vessel honours a fictional truck from a 1986 John Carpenter film, and a piece of
        Southern frying serves as a fair counterweight in the lineage. The word also
        carries its older meaning, which is to keep one's mouth shut, and which the
        Captain has been known to do for entire weekends at a stretch.
      </p>
      <p>
        Captain Mack accepted the designation without comment, which the Club took as
        ratification.
      </p>

    </div>
  </section>

</BaseLayout>

<style>
.vessel-header {
  background: var(--bg-deep);
  color: var(--fg-on-deep);
  padding-block: var(--space-9) var(--space-8);
}
.back-link {
  display: inline-block;
  font-family: var(--font-sans);
  font-size: 12px;
  font-weight: 600;
  letter-spacing: var(--tracking-wide);
  text-transform: uppercase;
  color: var(--brass-200);
  text-decoration: none;
  margin-bottom: var(--space-5);
  transition: color var(--dur-fast) var(--ease-out);
}
.back-link:hover { color: var(--sail-50); }
.vessel-badges { display: flex; gap: var(--space-2); margin-bottom: var(--space-4); flex-wrap: wrap; }
.vessel-header h1 {
  color: var(--sail-50);
  font-size: clamp(2.4rem, 5vw, var(--fs-display));
  margin-bottom: var(--space-4);
}
.vessel-lead {
  color: var(--fg-on-deep-muted);
  max-width: 58ch;
}

.vessel-photo-full {
  background: var(--navy-900);
  height: 480px;
  overflow: hidden;
}
.vessel-photo-full img {
  width: 100%;
  height: 100%;
  object-fit: cover;
  object-position: center 55%;
  opacity: 0.9;
}

.bow-shot {
  margin-block: var(--space-7);
  border-radius: var(--r-1);
  overflow: hidden;
  background: var(--navy-900);
}
.bow-shot img {
  width: 100%;
  height: auto;
  display: block;
}

@media (max-width: 900px) {
  .vessel-photo-full { height: 300px; }
}
</style>
